WEBVTT

00:00.834 --> 00:04.643
This week we are wrapping up our Advent and Christmas Tide series here.

00:04.963 --> 00:20.178
Now for the last six weeks or so we have been going through the O antiphons, which became the verses of O come, O come Emmanuel, to guide our study of Jesus and how his coming and his incarnation transforms our lives and our world.

00:20.866 --> 00:24.210
We're looking today at Jesus as the Lord of Might.

00:24.550 --> 00:37.585
And the verse that we sang just a little bit ago is, O come, O come, great Lord of Might, who two thy tribes on Sinai's height in ancient times did give the law in cloud and majesty and awe.

00:38.967 --> 00:49.138
So this week, Tuesday, actually specifically, is also Epiphany, which is a holiday on the church calendar which commemorates the visitation of the Magi to the Christ child.

00:49.698 --> 00:55.446
Epiphany comes from the Greek word Epiphania, which means appearance or manifestation.

00:56.147 --> 01:02.175
This is actually the word that is used most often in the New Testament to talk about Christ's second coming.

01:02.876 --> 01:07.002
And so you see perhaps one of the connections there with Jesus as Lord of might.

01:07.903 --> 01:15.954
Now we're going to be looking at a couple of passages today, Exodus 19, verses 16 to 19, and Matthew 2, verses 1 to 12.

01:16.450 --> 01:19.853
Now, as we prepare to open God's word together today, let's pray.

01:21.655 --> 01:28.942
God, Father, Son, and Holy Spirit, open our ears, calm our thoughts, open our hearts.

01:30.043 --> 01:31.464
We desire to hear from you.

01:32.485 --> 01:37.330
Speak through me, Lord, the words that you would have us here in silence, anything in me that is not of you.

01:38.411 --> 01:42.795
May the words of my mouth and the meditations of our hearts be acceptable and pleasing to you.

01:42.835 --> 01:45.277
O Lord, our rock and our Redeemer.

01:45.998 --> 01:46.418
Amen.

01:47.650 --> 01:52.277
So just a bit of a preface here before we jump right into Exodus 19.

01:52.317 --> 01:59.548
At this point of the book of Exodus, the people of Israel have been delivered out of Egypt and have been journeying in the wilderness.

02:00.329 --> 02:09.362
This week is actually accidentally slash providentially going to serve as a bit of an establishing scene for the sermon series that we're starting next week.

02:09.698 --> 02:15.285
You know how in a lot of movies, the movie will start with a set of scenes that are like really dramatic.

02:15.305 --> 02:20.131
The protagonist is up against the big evil bad and things like that.

02:20.151 --> 02:22.494
And you're just like, how is this at the beginning of the movie?

02:22.554 --> 02:25.037
And it just grows in anticipation and intensity.

02:25.838 --> 02:33.187
And then it hard cuts to the protagonist, I don't know, waking up two weeks earlier flashes across the bottom of the screen.

02:33.968 --> 02:38.514
This sermon series is a little bit like that for our next sermon series.

02:39.650 --> 02:42.274
Our next sermon series is called Beginning the Journey.

02:42.735 --> 02:45.459
We're going to be looking together at a few chapters from Exodus.

02:45.539 --> 02:48.784
Exodus 15 through 19 to 20-ish.

02:49.645 --> 02:56.656
As we look at the newly freed people of Israel, as they begin their journey in the wilderness and as they were learned to rely on God.

02:57.257 --> 03:05.810
Our passage today will be more or less revisited in six or so weeks at the end of that series, but the important intro info for today

03:05.922 --> 03:17.379
is that the Israelites have come to Mount Sinai, this mountain of the Lord, where God has promised to speak with Moses and his people, to give them the law and to establish a new covenant with his people of Israel.

03:18.320 --> 03:26.573
Now in preparation for this, God tells Moses that the Israelites must consecrate themselves, purify themselves, so that they can be near God's powerful presence.

03:27.654 --> 03:32.882
So the people are to wash their clothes, they are to erect barriers around the base of the mountain.

03:33.474 --> 03:44.645
For God himself will descend on the mountain in God's presence and holiness is so great that if anyone or anything touches the mountain, they must be put to death.

03:46.547 --> 03:51.873
The people cannot even leave their camp to approach the mountain until they hear the sound of trumpet.

03:52.734 --> 03:56.418
So that is where we are picking it up for a few verses starting at verse 16.

03:56.618 --> 03:57.298
Hear these words.

03:58.320 --> 04:00.722
On the morning of the third day after the consecration,

04:01.346 --> 04:06.612
There was thunder and lightning with a thick cloud over the mountain and a very loud trumpet blast.

04:07.292 --> 04:08.534
Everyone in the camp trembled.

04:09.555 --> 04:14.180
Then Moses led the people out of the camp to meet with God and they stood at the foot of the mountain.

04:14.901 --> 04:18.725
And Mount Sinai was covered with smoke because the Lord descended on it in fire.

04:19.786 --> 04:24.511
And smoke billowed up from it like smoke from a furnace in the whole mountain trembled violently.

04:25.692 --> 04:31.058
At the sound of the trumpet grew louder and louder, Moses spoke and the voice of God answered him.

04:32.450 --> 04:35.333
skipping forward several centuries to Matthew chapter two.

04:37.696 --> 04:46.967
After Jesus was born in Bethlehem in Judea during the time of King Herod Magi from the east came to Jerusalem and asked, where is the one who has been born king of the Jews?

04:47.568 --> 04:49.790
We saw his star when it rose and have come to worship him.

04:50.771 --> 04:53.775
When King Herod heard this, he was disturbed and all Jerusalem with him.

04:54.736 --> 05:00.082
When he had called together all the people's chief priests and teachers of the law, he asked them where the Messiah was to be born.

05:00.802 --> 05:04.487
In Bethlehem, in Judea, they replied, for this is what the prophet has written.

05:05.028 --> 05:09.674
But you, Bethlehem, in the land of Judah, are by no means least among the rulers of Judah.

05:10.255 --> 05:13.059
For out of you will come a ruler who will shepherd my people Israel."

05:13.920 --> 05:18.266
Then Herod called the Magi secretly and found out from them the exact time the star had appeared.

05:19.127 --> 05:23.033
He sent them to Bethlehem and said, go and make a careful search for the child.

05:23.734 --> 05:26.898
As soon as you find him, report to me so that I too may go and worship him.

05:27.682 --> 05:34.369
After they had heard the king, they went on their way, and the star they had seen when it rose, went ahead of them, until it stopped over the place where the child was.

05:35.370 --> 05:41.956
When they saw the star, they were overjoyed, and on coming to the house, they saw the child with his mother Mary, and they bowed down and worshiped him.

05:42.557 --> 05:46.540
Then they opened their treasures and presented him with gifts of gold, frankincense, and myrrh.

05:47.641 --> 05:52.927
And having been warned in a dream not to go back to Herod, they returned to their country by another route.

05:53.487 --> 05:54.548
This is the word of the Lord.

05:55.129 --> 05:56.370
Thanks be to God.

05:58.498 --> 06:04.405
So I was trying to figure out really this week where this sermon was heading on a deeper level.

06:05.026 --> 06:09.711
And what I feel like I've been given for us today is the idea of complacency.

06:10.472 --> 06:15.238
Complacency in relationships specifically or routine perhaps.

06:16.520 --> 06:23.068
I think this bears itself out within the context of this sermon as we wrap up this entire series and as we're looking forward to the next.

06:24.369 --> 06:28.434
So here's the kind of complacency I'm thinking about in relation to this.

06:29.122 --> 06:44.705
I'm thinking of instances where our relationships become so routine that we forget to truly live into them, that we forget to appreciate them, that we forget just really the weight of the relationships that we are in.

06:46.768 --> 06:48.050
Here's an example.

06:48.150 --> 06:55.922
One of my and Larissa's very good friends is a clarinetist, like DMA and clarinet performance, high caliber kind of person.

06:57.730 --> 07:05.228
I sometimes forget how impressive that is because the day to day we're just sending memes back and forth on Instagram.

07:06.211 --> 07:14.130
Or even if we discuss her teaching schedule or her rehearsal schedule, it kind of just becomes part and parcel, a little bit of routine.

07:15.010 --> 07:28.326
It's not until I really sit with what she's up to or get the chance to watch her or hear her perform that I'm reminded of like, oh, wow, no, she's actually really good at this.

07:29.748 --> 07:44.626
Maybe you have something like this with your friends or your kids or even your spouses, something that kind of resets and re-informs occasionally how you view them and how you interact with them, even though you know their skills and competencies always at some level.

07:45.186 --> 07:51.354
To get more specific, I do need to brag about my wife for a second, which I know is shocking to many of you.

07:52.555 --> 07:55.239
Don't worry, I did ask her if I could do this.

07:56.340 --> 08:02.348
So Larissa recently finished her first draft of the last chapter of her dissertation.

08:03.089 --> 08:11.359
And as head research assistant, I had the privilege of reading over that draft to give comments on clarity and flow.

08:12.320 --> 08:13.682
And now I am always aware.

08:13.954 --> 08:17.138
of how brilliant a scholar my wife is.

08:17.298 --> 08:28.953
But the day to day that kind of gets shuffled back in my brain because we're dealing with more pressing things like our son petting the cat even though the cat has signaled that he doesn't want to be pet.

08:29.413 --> 08:30.655
That happened this morning.

08:30.675 --> 08:32.397
That was a fun thing to deal with.

08:33.599 --> 08:39.626
But the brilliance of Larissa's mind gets shuffled back into my brain for the everyday.

08:39.807 --> 08:42.610
But when I read this chapter draft I was

08:43.490 --> 08:48.337
reminded of, convicted of even, how awesome she is.

08:48.397 --> 08:54.986
That's kind of what popped into my head as I was trying to discern what these passages were telling us today.

08:56.228 --> 09:01.876
Now the people of Israel have found themselves in a much more intense version of this.

09:02.757 --> 09:06.482
They have witnessed plagues brought on Egypt by God

09:06.658 --> 09:13.985
These plagues that show to everyone that God is immensely more powerful and immensely more in control than the gods of Egypt.

09:15.186 --> 09:32.643
They have seen God's power at work for them, delivering them from the Egyptians, parting the Red Sea and rescuing them, providing for them in all of their wanderings in the wilderness, despite all of their complaining, as God led them by a pillar of cloud and fire.

09:32.663 --> 09:35.346
But in spite of everything that's been done for them, I think they have

09:35.554 --> 09:42.283
grown perhaps a bit complacent in the routine in the day to day or week to week of surviving in the wilderness.

09:43.565 --> 09:58.706
But now, now they have come to this mountain in the desert where they have been told that this God, the God of their ancestors, the God who has brought them out of slavery and delivered them will himself be descending to make his presence known.

10:00.386 --> 10:08.219
They have consecrated themselves for three days by washing themselves and their clothes and abstaining from anything that would make them impure before God.

10:09.201 --> 10:19.058
They've been warned by Moses that if they even approach the mountain or set foot on it that they will be put to death because God's presence and holiness are so awesome and mighty.

10:21.154 --> 10:31.569
And our passage tells us on the morning of that third day, there was thunder and lightning with a thick cloud over the mountain and a very loud trumpet blast and everyone in the camp trembled.

10:34.032 --> 10:37.657
Now, do you all do that thing when there is a tornado warning?

10:38.598 --> 10:49.714
And the first thing that you do rather than going into your basement is to actually go outside to see for yourself how bad the weather actually is.

10:50.562 --> 10:56.590
Stand on your porch, watch the storm roll in before you have to decide if you actually have to go into the basement.

10:57.451 --> 10:58.492
Yeah, no, I know you do.

10:58.633 --> 10:59.373
I know you do.

11:00.134 --> 11:00.815
Not supposed to.

11:02.197 --> 11:03.178
We all do it.

11:03.198 --> 11:15.154
But if you ever done this, you know the feeling of trepidation but exhilaration as you watch the power of this storm system rolling.

11:18.306 --> 11:29.725
Now just think of how sometimes that trepidation, that exhilaration, that excitement morphs very quickly into dread and fear.

11:30.206 --> 11:38.739
If you see that the sky is indeed turning that lovely sickly shade of green and you know that this storm at the very least is going to be rough.

11:41.063 --> 11:45.170
You feel suddenly very small and helpless in the middle of the storm.

11:46.818 --> 11:51.022
Now I imagine that's what the Israelites were feeling as they approached this mountain.

11:51.122 --> 11:57.769
This mountain covered in smoke and fire with the ever-loudening sound of a trumpet blast like standing next to a tornado siren.

11:59.010 --> 12:05.556
The Lord Almighty, thunderously speaking to Moses from this cacophony in the presence of all the people.

12:06.257 --> 12:10.681
Cloud, majesty, and awe almost seem like an understatement.

12:13.063 --> 12:15.666
God then speaks directly

12:16.098 --> 12:20.385
to the gathered people, and he gives them the Ten Commandments.

12:20.805 --> 12:35.809
The people are so afraid that they tell Moses to go, to go speak to God on their behalf, to intercede for them, to stand in front of them, because they fear for their lives if God continues to speak to them directly.

12:38.353 --> 12:44.242
Now I love the pairing of this passage with Matthew 2.

12:45.122 --> 12:47.505
like the genie from the 90s Aladdin movie, you know?

12:47.846 --> 12:50.089
Phenomenal cosmic power.

12:51.430 --> 12:56.137
And an itty bitty baby.

12:56.157 --> 12:59.301
Now this is what I'm getting at with the whole complacency and routine thing.

12:59.421 --> 13:12.338
I have felt myself convicted recently to remember to recognize the fact that our God, the creator and sustainer of all things is God who descended with fire

13:12.418 --> 13:25.387
brimstone and cloud and thunder and lightning and a trumpet blast on this mountain, wants to be in relationship with me, wants to be in relationship with us.

13:26.470 --> 13:31.922
He wants us to come together as his people to worship him and to hear from him.

13:32.642 --> 13:44.016
This same God who appeared in this massive cloud and lightning and fire to the Israelites, was made incarnate as a human born of a woman to be a baby.

13:47.740 --> 14:00.015
Now much has said when we read this chapter from Matthew of how God brought these magi, these foreign astrologers to Bethlehem to behold Jesus, how God uses unexpected people for His glory.

14:00.035 --> 14:02.578
We've talked about that even within the sermon series.

14:03.586 --> 14:12.703
We read this story as a part of our Christmas, Christmas-tied epiphany rotation every year, and I think sometimes it gets lost.

14:14.948 --> 14:19.035
The majesty, the importance, the miracle of it all.

14:19.056 --> 14:22.482
We grow complacent in our understanding of it.

14:25.698 --> 14:28.721
So looking at Matthew 2, the Magi come to Jerusalem.

14:28.761 --> 14:36.169
They tell King Herod they have come to worship one who has been born king of the Jews because they saw his star when it rose in the east.

14:38.551 --> 14:53.266
Now due to the Babylonian exile of the people of Judah, it is actually highly likely that these Magi from wherever they were would have had access to and perhaps even read some of the Jewish scriptures and prophecies.

14:53.826 --> 14:56.169
So it's not unheard of.

14:56.189 --> 15:06.601
It's not too far a stretch to say that people outside of Jewish circles would have had an idea about the Jewish Messiah and where he was to be born, roughly.

15:08.884 --> 15:11.848
But that is all impressive in and of itself.

15:11.888 --> 15:20.338
But here's the part that has been really hitting me this season, as I've been looking at this, I've been preparing for this, is the star.

15:21.410 --> 15:38.416
You know, we read this, we decorate our Christmas things with this, you know, nice star that's kind of like floating in the air that the Magi are following and it magically floats over to the manger or the house or wherever it is.

15:40.539 --> 15:41.580
But here's the thing.

15:43.744 --> 15:50.674
There are extant records from China that record a supernova

15:51.522 --> 16:01.732
being visible in the sky for 70 days, around 54-ish BC, which is about the time that Jesus was actually born.

16:03.313 --> 16:21.330
And then there are also other astronomical records that show that there was a conjunction between Jupiter and Saturn a few years earlier in 7 BC that perhaps could have signaled to people who were watching the stars and the planets that a king

16:21.954 --> 16:27.841
Jupiter was to be born in the west, west of them, Saturn.

16:30.443 --> 16:50.706
Now, regardless of whether either of these are the star that is being referred to by the Magi, that's not the important part, but can we sit for just a bit in awe of the idea of God?

16:51.906 --> 17:01.859
shifting the structure of the universe to point people to a baby.

17:05.203 --> 17:20.402
God is timing the orbit of planets, maybe even blowing up a star, blowing up a star to point people

17:21.218 --> 17:34.814
who perhaps do not have true faith in him to point them to the birth of a child to a working-class couple from a tiny village in Galilee.

17:37.438 --> 17:44.506
The Lord of Might became incarnate as a helpless child.

17:44.746 --> 17:51.154
The Lord of Might moving through the wonders of the heavens to mark the birth of this child.

17:56.034 --> 18:00.802
There is more to this than just the immense cosmic significance, though.

18:02.785 --> 18:11.780
The Magize visitation to Jesus to present him with these gifts is also a callback to First Kings, the book of First Kings.

18:12.221 --> 18:22.898
You know, after Solomon, David's son is established as his father's successor, and the king of Israel, after Solomon builds the temple,

18:23.298 --> 18:35.796
The queen of Sheba, which is an ancient kingdom in the Arabian peninsula, the queen of Sheba makes a royal visit to Solomon and gives him spices and gold and precious stones the book First Kings tells us.

18:37.538 --> 18:46.130
Now, the gold and frankincense and myrrh that the mag I give to Jesus are not exact correlations of what the queen gives to Solomon.

18:46.946 --> 19:04.228
But the way in which the gospel writer Matthew sets this account up, the way that he tells it would have caused any well-read Jewish person to think of the Queen of Shiba's visit to Solomon, right?

19:04.268 --> 19:15.762
The Magi are a group of foreign royal dignitaries who are traveling to the region of Judea to bestow luxurious gifts upon a son of David.

19:17.058 --> 19:19.821
just as the Queen of Sheba did all those centuries before.

19:20.321 --> 19:25.866
Except, unlike the Queen of Sheba, the Magi are not ultimately going to the palace in Jerusalem.

19:25.886 --> 19:30.611
They show up to the palace in Jerusalem because they are here to herald a king.

19:33.514 --> 19:35.215
But they're not ultimately going to the palace.

19:35.235 --> 19:36.357
They don't ultimately end up there.

19:36.377 --> 19:46.226
They end up in the far-flung suburbs at a normal house to visit the child of a working-class family.

19:51.426 --> 19:58.256
And the other point that I want us to consider today, I think, is one of the greatest things about the incarnation.

19:59.758 --> 20:03.063
And that is that we have direct access to God.

20:05.046 --> 20:10.214
If we return to Exodus, we return to God speaking with Moses on Mount Sinai.

20:10.234 --> 20:12.658
We read this exchange starting at verse 20.

20:13.880 --> 20:17.886
The Lord descended to the top of Mount Sinai and called Moses to the top of the mountain.

20:18.547 --> 20:20.850
So Moses went up and the Lord said to him, go down.

20:21.122 --> 20:25.588
and warn the people so that they do not force their way through to see the Lord and many of them perish.

20:26.529 --> 20:31.556
Even the priests who approach the Lord must consecrate themselves so the Lord will break out against them.

20:31.576 --> 20:38.865
Moses said to the Lord, the people cannot come up Mount Sinai because you yourself warned us, put limits around the mountain and set it apart as holy.

20:40.067 --> 20:42.510
The Lord replied, go down and bring Aaron up with you.

20:43.411 --> 20:48.818
But the priests and the people must not force their way through to come up to the Lord or he will break out against them.

20:49.506 --> 20:51.368
So Moses went down to the people and told them.

20:53.611 --> 21:04.544
Now this scene on Mount Sinai here actually corresponds to how the tabernacle, the tent of meeting that the people had in the wilderness and ultimately the temple were to be set up.

21:06.066 --> 21:11.632
Only God's singular chosen has access to God's presence.

21:11.692 --> 21:13.234
Moses in this case.

21:13.890 --> 21:19.398
And this corresponds to the most holy place in the tabernacle and in the temple, where only the high priest could enter.

21:19.718 --> 21:22.282
And even then, the high priest could only enter once a year.

21:22.582 --> 21:43.090
And even then, the high priest had to have a rope tied around his waist, so that if he was in any way impure before the presence of God and was struck down, his fellow priests could drag his lifeless body out, so as not to defile the presence of the most holy place.

21:46.626 --> 21:52.292
Even the one who intercedes on the people's behalf was in danger.

21:54.915 --> 22:00.862
The elders of the people have access to the mountain, but they cannot summit the mountain where Moses is speaking to God.

22:00.882 --> 22:11.474
This corresponds with the holy place, the priest's court, where the priests who serve in the tabernacle in the temple can enter and perform rituals, but the normal people cannot.

22:12.642 --> 22:23.797
And finally, the people of Israel are gathered at the foot of the mountain, which corresponds to the outer courts of the temple and the tabernacle, where the normal people, the everyday people can come and offer sacrifices to God.

22:25.699 --> 22:40.338
But with the incarnation, with Christ's coming, that division is removed because Jesus himself is the ultimate intercessor, an unlike

22:40.514 --> 22:49.965
Any human intercessor, be that Moses, be that a high priest, Jesus does not need to fear death in the presence of God because He is Himself God.

22:52.447 --> 22:55.371
He is one person of the triune Godhead.

22:58.294 --> 23:05.522
The Magi can come and offer gifts to God directly in the Christ child.

23:07.010 --> 23:10.816
This is a foretaste of what happens when Jesus dies on the cross.

23:12.258 --> 23:26.079
The curtain that separates the holy place from the most holy place in the temple is torn in two, removing any barrier that we may have to God.

23:28.002 --> 23:30.866
My friends, we can talk to God.

23:31.522 --> 23:37.112
We have the presence of God in dwelling within us by the power and the presence of the Holy Spirit.

23:37.132 --> 23:44.786
This is the same God who caused all these phenomena that made the people of Israel tremble in fear when they came near his presence.

23:45.187 --> 23:55.506
This is the same God who came to earth as a child taking on the form of a servant or a slave even as Paul says in Philippians being made in appearance of a man.

23:55.746 --> 24:08.724
This is the same God who shifted the structure of the universe to herald the birth of a baby.

24:08.744 --> 24:17.256
But if we return to the idea of routine and complacency, I think we forget this.

24:18.838 --> 24:19.679
Not intentionally.

24:19.699 --> 24:24.626
I don't think, I don't think for the most part we forget this intentionally.

24:25.730 --> 24:32.137
But we forget, we lose the majesty of Christ in our routine.

24:34.779 --> 24:36.441
But it's not, it's not just us.

24:37.682 --> 24:38.683
The Israelites forgot.

24:40.085 --> 24:40.946
Oh boy, do they forget.

24:42.127 --> 24:49.775
Despite all of this fear and trembling and oh no Moses, we can't speak directly with God.

24:49.815 --> 24:51.677
You must go and intercede for us.

24:51.997 --> 24:52.978
Do you know

24:53.346 --> 24:58.571
Remember what they did before Moses even came down the mountain?

24:58.611 --> 25:02.235
They made the golden calf.

25:03.896 --> 25:11.524
They turned away from the God whose presence was right next to them on a mountain.

25:11.564 --> 25:22.194
The whole Bible is full of account after account after account of God's people, forgetting

25:22.466 --> 25:27.194
who it is that leads them, who it is that they worship, whose laws they follow.

25:29.298 --> 25:31.161
Jesus' disciples screw up.

25:33.164 --> 25:41.458
That's what most of Jesus' words are addressing in a lot of the Gospels is the disciples messing it up time after time.

25:43.394 --> 25:46.897
The religious leaders of Jesus' day mess up.

25:46.957 --> 25:50.441
Most of them do not recognize Jesus as the Messiah.

25:50.481 --> 25:53.584
In fact, they outright reject Him as the Messiah.

25:54.585 --> 25:57.627
The early church screwed up all the time.

25:57.948 --> 26:01.131
They forgot who they were and what they were being called to.

26:01.191 --> 26:05.875
That's why most of the letters in the New Testament exist.

26:05.895 --> 26:13.202
It's because Paul and Peter and the other apostles are writing to churches to remind them to get their act together.

26:14.370 --> 26:15.992
It's not just us, my friends.

26:16.012 --> 26:17.294
It's not unique to us.

26:17.374 --> 26:18.716
It's not unique to our time.

26:18.776 --> 26:24.504
This is the story of God's people, as fallen, broken sinners.

26:24.604 --> 26:25.766
We forget.

26:26.927 --> 26:43.250
We need to be reminded of God's power, of who God is, how awesome He is, how mighty He is, and how in His might Jesus humbled Himself to become incarnate as a human.

26:46.946 --> 26:47.988
No, I'm not saying.

26:48.588 --> 26:49.209
Don't get me wrong.

26:49.229 --> 26:55.158
I'm not saying that we need to come in here every week with intense fear and trembling.

26:56.681 --> 27:05.193
Because while we do need to recognize and be reminded of the might and the majesty of Christ whom we worship and adore, we do not have to fear.

27:07.096 --> 27:13.746
Belief in Christ as our Lord and Savior, as the Heideberg Catechism puts it in question and answer 59,

27:14.306 --> 27:18.151
belief in Christ means that in Christ we are righteous.

27:18.191 --> 27:25.501
We are made right before God and we are heirs to life everlasting.

27:28.826 --> 27:33.011
We need not fear as the Israelites did because Christ intercedes for us.

27:34.573 --> 27:41.042
Moses interceded for the people when they were too afraid to be spoken to directly by God and Christ

27:41.218 --> 27:47.385
Christ is the perfect mediator, the perfect intercessor who intercedes to God for us on our behalf.

27:49.207 --> 27:52.110
We can therefore come boldly to God's throne of grace.

27:53.191 --> 27:59.819
We're also recognizing the power of God and of our own sins before Him.

28:03.763 --> 28:06.506
Last week, Pastor Michael referenced the Chronicles of Narnia.

28:06.947 --> 28:08.028
I'm gonna do it again.

28:08.068 --> 28:09.650
We're gonna get a nice double header here.

28:10.658 --> 28:21.375
I thought of the exchange in the lion, the witch, and the wardrobe between Mr. and Mrs. Beaver and the children when I was thinking of this sermon.

28:23.518 --> 28:31.130
The children, the pevency children are hearing about Aslan the lion, the Christ figure in the series for the first time.

28:34.134 --> 28:39.122
And Susan confesses that she is afraid to meet a lion.

28:40.322 --> 29:00.282
which Mrs. Beaver says, well, yes, of course, no one can stand in Aslan's presence without their knees knocking together unless they're incredibly brave or incredibly silly, which then prompts Lucy to ask, then he isn't safe, to which Mr. Beaver then reapplies safe.

29:01.203 --> 29:02.704
Who said anything about safe?

29:02.765 --> 29:06.148
Of course he's not safe, but he's good.

29:07.429 --> 29:08.210
He's the king.

29:10.434 --> 29:22.273
Or is the 2005 movie adaptation tweaks that at the end of the movie, Mr. Thomas tells Lucy, well, he's not a tame lion, but he is good.

29:25.098 --> 29:28.704
Jesus Christ, God Almighty in the flesh.

29:31.548 --> 29:34.153
Well, we need to be reminded of his might and justice.

29:34.173 --> 29:37.458
We can also take solace in his love for us.

29:39.170 --> 29:39.470
C.S.

29:39.510 --> 29:44.156
Lewis, the author of The Chronicles of Narnia, writes this in his book, Mirror Christianity.

29:45.217 --> 29:57.492
The great thing to remember is that, though our feelings come and go, Jesus' love, Christ's love for us does not.

29:57.512 --> 30:05.362
It is not weirried by our sins, it is not weirried by our indifference, our complacency, our routine perhaps.

30:06.818 --> 30:17.192
And therefore it is quite relentless in its determination that we should be cured of those sins, at whatever cost to us, at whatever cost to Jesus.

30:19.615 --> 30:23.941
My friends, this is our Lord of might whose birth we are celebrating.

30:25.183 --> 30:27.666
He humbled himself to become incarnate.

30:28.130 --> 30:31.113
because of his love and his grace for us.

30:31.153 --> 30:34.897
He gave his life to save us from our sins.

30:34.957 --> 30:40.443
He has ascended and will return in all of his might to usher in the new creation.

30:41.925 --> 30:43.186
How can we not praise him?

30:43.927 --> 30:45.189
How can we not give thanks?

30:48.592 --> 30:53.778
Now, yes, we will inevitably lose our sense of awe in the routine.

30:55.746 --> 30:58.869
but let us strive to remind ourselves of this.

31:01.813 --> 31:09.261
May we, like the Magi, come and behold him, the light of the world.

31:09.881 --> 31:13.605
May we behold God in the flesh who gave himself for us.

31:13.645 --> 31:25.298
May we come with fear and trembling, yes, but may we come to him with the boldness that we are granted by our salvation

31:26.018 --> 31:26.686
in Christ.

31:28.387 --> 31:28.690
Amen.

